<TEXT>
music publishers filed a class action lawsuit 
on monday against the sony corp claiming the manufacturers 
digital audio tape machines promote illegal home taping of music 
the lawsuit filed in federal court in new york city seeks to 
block the importation and sale of the sony dat equipment the 
sophisticated machines which yield near perfect duplications of 
recorded music went on sale in the united states last month 
sony is not the sole exporter of the machines but leads the 
field 
this equipment was truly designed and intended for the purpose 
of infringing copy rights said marvin frankel an attorney 
representing an estimated 40000 songwriters and 450000 copy 
rights 
virtually everybody who is likely to buy this equipment will 
be using it for infringement purposes frankel said 
a call made after hours to sony headquarters in new york was 
unanswered 
the lawsuit states that sony is inaugurating a new era in 
unauthorized home taping of copyrighted musical compositions 
the japanese electronics giant the suit alleges is actively 
promoting the ability of dat recorders to make perfect digital 
copies of compact discs 
the suit cites a recent survey sponsored by a music industry 
trade organization showing that dat owners intend to use the 
equipment to tape prerecorded music 
unlike analog tape recording machines digital technology 
provides for immaculate duplication of compact discs and of 
subsequent generations of dat cassettes 
the complaint asked the court to find that unauthorized dat 
taping violates the federal copyright statute the suit maintains 
such taping hurts sales of compact discs cassettes and records 
costing the industry substantial copyright revenues 
the lawsuit names sony corp sony usa inc and sony corp of 
america as defendants it was filed on behalf of sammy cahn jac 
music co inc fort knox music inc trio music co inc and teer 
international inc 
the announcement of the lawsuits filing was made at the annual 
meeting of the national music publishers association edward 
murphy president of the organization said the group will offer 
assistance to the plaintiffs in the lawsuit 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

