an agriculture department economist says 
japans resistance to opening its door to rice imports has deep 
roots 
the united states has been pressuring japan to abandon its 
policy against rice imports as a step toward trade liberalization 
william coyle of the departments economic research service said 
japans agricultural policy is woven into the countrys culture 
but coyle added in the july issue of farmline magazine that some 
changes are taking place as urban dwellers ties with the 
countryside weaken the yen appreciates in relation to other 
currencies and ruralurban competition for land intensifies 
coyle also noted some differences japan has 24 people per acre 
of cropland compared with 12 in the united states 
japan has 4 million farms averaging 325 acres each compared 
with 2 million averaging 463 acres in the united states 
in terms of value rice is the most significant japanese crop 
followed by livestock products both meat and milk vegetables 
and fruit japan is accustomed to importing foods other than rice 
and about 70 percent of the livestock feed is imported 
japan has had a policy of being selfsufficient in rice since 
the 1940s at the beginning of world war ii japan was a rice 
importer and many older japanese remember the food shortages 
during and immediately after the war 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
imports of beef and veal are expected to 
increase only slightly if at all this year according to 
agriculture department forecasts 
