<TEXT>
christian science officials contributed to the 
death of robyn twitchell by discouraging his parents from calling a 
doctor an inquest concluded three years ago 
david and ginger twitchell lifelong christian scientists were 
convicted wednesday of manslaughter in the april 1986 death of 
2yearold robyn by relying solely on prayer to treat the boy 
during a fiveday illness 
they were sentenced to 10 years probation on friday and ordered 
to take their three remaining children for regular medical exams 
in a 1987 report west roxbury district court judge lawrence d 
shubow found that the churchs chief spokesman nathan talbot a 
christian science nurse and a church practitioner contributed 
to robyns death by acting recklessly and without legal excuse 
the three were never indicted by the grand jury investigating 
the case 
shubows 35page report was impounded since its completion in 
1987 but was released friday by superior court judge sandra hamlin 
who presided at the twitchells manslaughter trial 
talbot was faulted for telling the twitchells to call a funeral 
home rather than the police or the medical examiner when the couple 
called talbot to say robyn had died talbot said today that the 
church no longer told followers to call a funeral home in such 
circumstances 
an autopsy showed the boy suffered from a congenital defect that 
had caused a bowel obstruction 
calling police or the medical examiner would have in normal 
course initiated a lifesaving response shubow wrote the 
delays in reporting robyns plight erased his remaining chance to 
survive 
linda blaisdell a church nurse recommended to the couple by 
talbot had earlier wrongfully prescribed food for robyn which 
probably worsened his illness shubow wrote 
