<TEXT>
many of the temporary workers taking the 
nations census may be ineligible for unemployment compensation 
when their jobs end because of a recent moneysaving change in the 
law 
the actual number of people affected is hard to estimate because 
rules for unemployment compensation eligibility vary from state to 
state neither congressional or census spokesmen would estimate the 
number affected 
in the past temporary census jobs have counted toward 
eligibility for unemployment compensation just as any other job 
however this year an appropriations bill signed by president 
bush on may 25 set an april 20 cutoff on census workers getting 
credit toward unemployment temporary census work done after that 
date doesnt count when they are eventually laid off and apply for 
unemployment benefits 
how that cutoff affects individual workers depends on the 
unemployment eligibility rules in their states some states for 
example require 26 weeks of work before someone becomes eligible 
people who havent accumulated that before april 20 would not be 
able to collect benefits 
april 20 was the deadline for people sending in their mailed 
census forms meaning the credit cutoff applies primarily to the 
thousands of temporary field workers who were sent doortodoor to 
track down people who did not apply much of that work has now been 
finished although followup operations are expected to continue at 
least through fall in some areas 
warren kane of the senate appropriations committee which 
inserted the provision into a financial bill said the action made 
70 million available for completing the national head count 
the low response rate to the mailed portion of the census meant 
more staff had to be hired to go door to door and the committee 
had to find money to cover that hiring 
in looking at census finances he said the committee found that 
when the bureau hired temporary workers it was setting money aside 
to cover their later unemployment costs when the jobs ended by 
cutting off unemployment credit at april 20 the committee 
eliminated the need for those funds which then became available 
for hiring more temporary workers kane said 
</TEXT>
