a market system without western credits and wants help from the 
industrial powers to stop soviet economic decline 
the most prominent conservative in the soviet leadership yegor 
k ligachev said the west could try to push moscow in a direction 
he opposes 
if conditions are attached to these lines of credit such 
as a move toward a free market economy or private property then 
ligachev is against it he said at the party congress 
foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze was more conciliatory 
we understand if no one wants to take a risk the usa isnt 
speaking in favor of development of economic cooperation if reform 
doesnt proceed as we plan he said 
such aid he said would be advantageous for us and the 
west 
soviet officials offered their first detailed list of what kind 
of help they want from the west 
shakhnazarov said the soviet union would like western technology 
for quick construction of small businesses to produce consumer 
goods and food items in short supply gorbachev has made 
improvements in both a top priority 
the soviet economy also suffers from inflation and a huge budget 
deficit 
help in organizing market mechanisms such as banking finance 
and management also are priorities the gorbachev aide said 
in return shakhnazarov said moscow could offer the west help 
in converting the defense industry to produce civilian goods 
gorbachev has launched a program to tap highly developed defense 
plants to assist the civilian sector 
the leaders of west germany and france advocate helping the 
soviet union despite disagreements over cuba and have called for 
15 billion in aid to bolster reform plans 
asked whether the soviet union would cut aid to cuba 
shevardnadze said that was strictly a question of bilateral 
relations and did not indicate the governments plans 
credits would help soviet businesses pay bills to western 
companies the soviet union traditionally has been punctual in 
making such payments and recent delays have eroded confidence among 
foreign investors 
west germany already has granted an unconditional loan of 31 
billion 
estimates of how much money the soviet union would need to begin 
to stabilize its economy range from 5 billion to 20 billion 
