<TEXT>
the doctor who performed the worlds first 
successful liver transplant was recovering monday following surgery 
to remove blockage in one of his coronary arteries officials said 
dr thomas e starzl 64 was alert and resting comfortably at 
presbyterianuniversity hospital where he has performed hundreds 
of transplants during the past nine years said dr bruce wilson 
director of the university of pittsburghs heart institute 
doctors removed a severe blockage from starzls right coronary 
artery sunday after he complained of chest pains wilson said the 
artery was 99 percent blocked 
hes doing quite well wilson told reporters we expect a 
speedy recovery 
because the blockage was not total starzls heart muscle did 
not appear to be damaged wilson said the two remaining arteries 
look pretty normal he said 
starzl gained attention in 1967 when he performed the worlds 
first successful liver transplant at the university of colorado he 
also pioneered the development of a medical team that performed 200 
kidney transplants at colorado general and denver veterans 
administration hospitals 
in 1981 starzl began work at the university of pittsburgh 
which he helped make the worlds premier transplant center last 
year the hospital performed more than 460 liver transplants and 
210 kidney transplants 
wilson said a severe blockage of the kind starzl had can occur 
suddenly when blood strips away crusted plaque lining the arteries 
and causes a larger buildup farther along in the artery people who 
disregard the first symptoms of pain run the risk of a complete 
blockage which can cause a heart attack and permanent damage he 
said 
wilson said he will monitor starzls condition the next few days 
and ask him to restrict his work schedule but he added it may be 
difficult to persuade the energetic surgeon to slow down 
a person like tom starzl might have more stress if you inhibit 
him he said 
