<DOCNO> AP900709-0118 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
outofpocket health expenses are taking the 
same size bite out of americans incomes as they were in the early 
1970s and even less than in 1960 according to a team of 
government researchers 
over the past three decades as health costs have climbed the 
government and employers have shared most of the increased costs 
the health care financing administration researchers reported 
private insurance has been providing more benefits largely 
because states are requiring more coverage but employers have been 
unsuccessful in shifting the costs of better coverage to workers 
said economist katharine r levit 
however she predicts that will change 
businesses are essentially being squeezed by medical costs 
on the employer side and by competition on the price side she 
said some reconciliation of the problem is going to have to 
occur 
but while many business leaders and some politicians have been 
calling for changes in the nations health care system we as 
individuals dont feel the pressure yet levit said and until 
we do we wont join the ranks of business and government in 
clamoring for changes 
in 1988 spending from all sources for health care in the united 
states was nearly 540 billion more than 11 percent of the gross 
national product that year levit and two colleagues reported in an 
article published in the summer issue of health affairs a 
quarterly journal on health policy 
the figures tallied by levit mark freeland and dan waldo are 
the latest comprehensive figures available they said 
national health expenditures have grown at an average annual 
rate of 11 percent over the past three decades and 104 percent 
from 1987 to 1988 
americans used about 5 percent of their aftertax income in 1988 
on health care expenses including their share of insurance 
premiums and outofpocket costs to meet deductibles and pay for 
medical care not covered by insurance 
this proportion is the same as in 197273 and lower than the 61 
percent of aftertax income used for health care expenses in 
196061 the researchers reported 
since 196465 health spending has grown from 42 percent of all 
federal expenditures to nearly 14 percent in 1987 levit said for 
state and local expenditures combined health spending has grown 
from 74 percent to 13 percent over the same period she said 
businesses have seen their share of health insurance premiums 
increase from 2 percent of total employer compensation in 1965 to 6 
percent in 1987 levit said 
</TEXT>
