<TEXT>
the ageold question of why birds of a 
feather flock together could be answered with a few equations and a 
computer a zoology professor said monday 
zoologist frank h heppner of the university of rhode island and 
ulf grenander a brown university applied mathematician have 
produced flocks of simulated birds by plugging in a few numbers 
building on the work of others who have shown that in a branch of 
mathematics that deals with chaos there is order 
weve got something here that looks like a bird flock or a 
swarm of bees heppner said so we know we can produce that 
kind of behavior but were not sure why it works the way it does 
the implications are tremendous say those familiar with the 
field new ways to control swarms of planes around busy airports 
crowd control even simpler computer animation 
the beauty is that the complex behavior comes from some simple 
rules interacting with each other said christopher langton a 
mathematician with los alamos national laboratory in new mexico 
any minor change is magnified through the chain much like one bird 
swerving suddenly can divert the whole flock 
thats what chaos is all about he said 
heppner 49 who calls himself just a simple country scientist 
i like to work on things i can see spent about 15 years 
pursuing theories that flocks needed a leader before a computer 
game changed his thinking in 1987 
the game life uses a few simple rules to make squares 
interact on a screen heppner made up some rules and when he tried 
to generate patterns across the screen he realized this is a bird 
flock 
he concluded that it explained the actions of a flock of 
thousands of starlings for instance much better than looking for 
a bird leader 
he hooked up with grenander an amateur bird watcher and 
graduate student daniel f potter and they wrote equations and a 
computer program 
the simple rules were that birds like to be with each other but 
not too close they probably will try to keep up with each other 
and they will be attracted to something such as a roost 
then based on heppners reallife studies they plugged in 
numbers 
sometimes the little triangles representing birds would fly off 
their perch on a simulated wire and come together only to fly 
apart again other times they would come together but fly off the 
screen nine out of 10 times the birds didnt do anything 
heppner said 
but sometimes the numbers would work and the birds would swoop 
around the roost in complicated but cohesive patterns 
its very dramatic when you see it on the screen said 
heppner 
theres been a lot of serendipity with this he said 
were really at the stage of playing with it 
the current model looks down on the simulated birds next is to 
create a threedimensional model that can be viewed sideways 
heppner says the team then will compare it with videotapes of real 
flocks 
heppner said he has had calls from people studying bee swarms 
and from federal aviation administration researchers wondering if 
pilots given more information about other planes in their area 
might naturally slide into landing formation without as much 
intervention from controllers 
a researcher from a military thinktank even called to see if 
the teams work might help explain if soldiers without a leader 
could function as a unit 
what the birds would indicate is that yeah they probably 
could reach a pretty decent decision heppner said 
</TEXT>
