<TEXT>
nasa on monday grounded two veteran 
shuttle crew commanders one involved in a fatal collision of stunt 
planes at a weekend air show and one accused of flying too close to 
an airliner 
navy cmdr robert l hoot gibson and navy capt david m 
walker were grounded for violations of johnson space center flight 
crew operations guidelines nasa said gibson was grounded for one 
year walker for 60 days 
this is the first time we have removed crew members from 
flights for disciplinary reasons said nasa spokesman jeff carr 
gibson 43 piloted an eightday challenger mission in 1984 and 
commanded the 1986 columbia mission and the december 1988 atlantis 
mission 
walker piloted a space shuttle flight in 1984 and was commander 
of the space shuttle atlantis during a fourday flight in may 1989 
nasa said gibson was removed from shuttle flight assignments and 
from t38 jet trainer flight status for one year for violating a 
policy that restricts highrisk recreational activities for 
astronauts named to flight crews 
gibsons stunt plane on saturday collided with another plane 
during a texas airshow the second craft hurtled into a cornfield 
and killed its pilot henry w jones jr 69 a retired fighter 
pilot from newport news va 
gibson landed his plane safely at the new braunfels municipal 
airport 25 miles northeast of san antonio 
donald r puddy director of flight crew operations said 
gibsons participation in the event was a clear violation of 
safety 
walker was scheduled to command a department of defense mission 
in march 1991 he was replaced on the flight and suspended from 
t38 flight status nasa said 
walker was suspended for a may 1989 incident in which the pilot 
of a pan am airbus 310 reported a near midair collision 
between his aircraft and a t38 jet flown by walker near 
washingtons dulles international airport 
a near collision is generally reported when two planes come 
within 500 feet of each other and either pilot feels the planes 
were in danger of colliding 
the federal aviation administration said air traffic controllers 
filed a pilot deviation report accusing walker of violating 
flight procedures it said the planes came within 100 feet 
vertically but that it was not clear how near the planes were at 
their closest point 
walker had descended to 7000 feet the assigned altitude of 
the pan am airliner when a controller ordered him to climb to 
8000 feet faa spokesman john leyden said at the time 
carr said the timing of the two groundings was an incredible 
coincidence 
the decision to ground walker was made a week ago but the 
announcement was delayed while authorities searched for a 
replacement for him on next years pentagon shuttle flight carr 
said 
walker had come up for disciplinary action review because of a 
number of aircraft operating infractions including the pan am 
incident carr said he refused to disclose any of the other 
infractions 
