a federal judge told attorneys monday he doubted 
he would take action in a lawsuit challenging georgias 
majorityrule vote before next weeks state primary elections 
us district judge richard c freeman addressed the timeliness 
of the suit at the end of the first day of testimony in the case 
david walbert an attorney representing the state had asked 
freeman if tuesdays session could start a few hours later than 
scheduled freeman responded the longer we wait the harder it 
will be to get this done i dont think it will be done anyway 
to be perfectly frank 
freeman noted that the lawsuit challenging the majorityvote 
requirement was filed in may though a motion asking him to stop 
the use of the requirement in the july 17 primary was filed only 
last week at the last minute 
the lawsuit filed by a group of black officials contends that 
the 1964 majority vote law which requires a runoff when one 
candidate fails to win a majority effectively keeps blacks out of 
public office 
the lawsuit seeks to replace the current system with a plurality 
method which would give the election to the candidate who wins the 
most votes 
the plaintiffs say the majorityvote requirement hurts black 
candidates because it is difficult for them to win more than 50 
percent of the vote in a state that is about threequarters white 
freeman did not indicate if he was leaning toward either side in 
deciding the suit 
laughlin mcdonald an american civil liberties union attorney 
representing the plaintiffs said filing the suit before the 
election gives the plaintiffs the option if the judge rules 
against them of maintaining their objections to the election 
results and seeking to have them changed afterward 
the first witness in the case was a political scientist from the 
california institute of technology who testified there were 
numerous indications that the georgia legislature had racial 
motivations in enacting the majorityvote law 
j morgan kousser a professor of history and social science and 
the author of a book on southern politics said state rep denmark 
groover pushed the majorityvote law through the legislature after 
national civil rights legislation led to the abolition of the 
states county unit election system that system resembling the 
electoral college system of choosing presidents awarded one to 
three units to a candidate for each county he carried 
kousser said groover was at the time an avowed segregationist 
groover who lost his legislative seat in 1958 to a moderate 
white candidate with considerable black support had publicly 
complained about black block voting according to kousser 
groover returned to the legislature in 1962 in 1984 kousser 
said groover admitted that in the early 1960s i was a 
segregationist i had my prejudices and i dont mind admitting 
it 
mcdonald said he does not plan to call groover as a witness 
kousser said there were other signs that lawmakers in 1964 
wanted to keep blacks out of public office including an attempt to 
stiffen the literacy test for voter registration 
