<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
july 29 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
gannett co inc says it expects 
secondquarter earnings to be lower than a year earlier its first 
quarterly drop since the company went public 22 years ago 
sheila gibbons a spokeswoman for the nations biggest newspaper 
company said july 6 that gannett would issue its actual earnings 
report for the apriljune period in a few weeks 
douglas mccorkindale vice chairman and chief financial officer 
first projected an earnings decline during an interview published 
in july 6 editions of the wall street journal 
mccorkindale said he could not disagree with wall street 
analysts who forecast that gannetts net income would be below the 
1121 million or 70 cents a share of the yearearlier quarter 
however he would not predict specific earnings figures 
a decline in earnings would indicate how gannett is being 
affected by a slump that has hit the entire newspaper industry a 
number of wall street analysts have forecast declines for earnings 
of many newspaper publishers because of the soft ad revenue 
we started to see softness in advertising business in 1989 
and have been getting softer in the last eight to 12 months 
mccorkindale said we have not seen any signs of improved 
business conditions 
the expected earnings decline would come at a difficult time for 
gannett 
the gannett foundation the companys largest shareholder 
announced april 26 that it planned to sell its 10 percent stake a 
weak stock price could make the company a possible takeover target 
the foundation headed by former gannett chairman allen 
neuharth is sorting through potential bidders 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
ralph ingersoll ii agreed to give up control of 
his us newspapers after failing to make an interest payment on 
junk bonds 
the publisher said he would trade his us interests and their 
troublesome debt to his investment partners in exchange for control 
of a smaller group of european newspapers 
ingersoll whose us properties included the new haven conn 
register and the shortlived st louis sun said the july 2 deal 
was driven by a desire to get more involved in european publishing 
but bankers and investors with knowledge of the publisher said 
ingersoll was facing the same reckoning as robert campeau and 
donald trump who also used junk bond financing to build business 
empires but couldnt handle their massive interest payments 
he has an unworkable balance sheet said james rubin an 
analyst at md sass investors services a new york investment firm 
that successfully urged bondholders to reject ingersolls bid to 
work out his debt troubles this spring 
rubin said ingersoll took on too much debt in buying daily and 
weekly newspapers and was hurt further by the nationwide slump in 
advertising revenue 
ingersoll is relinquishing his stake in three companies that 
publish dozens of daily and weekly newspapers to the new york 
investment firm em warburg pincus amp co the two had been joint 
owners although ingersoll had voting control 
warburg pincus gains full control of ingersoll newspapers inc 
which publishes nine dailies and 53 weeklies new haven acquisition 
co publisher of the register and community newspapers inc 
which has newspapers in ohio and on new yorks long island 
ingersoll president robert jelenic formerly secondincommand 
was made chief executive officer of the new company 
ingersoll meanwhile will gain control of a group of british 
and irish newspapers that he controlled jointly with warburg 
pincus 
the announcement came as community newspapers said it would not 
make a july 1 interest payment on its 125 million in 13 percent 
junk bonds ingersoll had been trying for months to buy back the 
bonds at a steep discount to alleviate his debt burden 
in a telephone interview ingersoll said the three us 
companies were on track to make 100 million in profits before 
taxes and interest this year on revenue of 400 million 
we are having a record year despite the economy he said 
the companies could have serviced their debt if not for the 
collapse of the junk bond market which hit bonds like community 
newspapers especially hard ingersoll said 
the announcement comes a little more than two months after 
ingersoll folded the st louis sun a new tabloid that he hoped 
would revolutionize the slumping newspaper market by using new 
technology and marketing strategies 
the british and irish newspapers ingersoll is gaining have 
combined circulations exceeding 1 million and annual revenue of 
178 million 
europe offers great opportunities because of the planned 
dropping of trade barriers in western europe and the spread of 
freemarket economies in the east ingersoll said 
</TEXT>
