<TEXT>
new york state is preparing to enter the 
negotiations between the daily news and its 10 unions the head of 
the state mediation board said july 3 
the chairman of the panel hezekiah brown said that because of 
union support for state intervention he would begin the process 
leading to a formal state inquiry into contract negotiations at the 
tabloid 
brown would look at the negotiations between the paper and the 
unions if he determined it could be helpful to a settlement he 
would recommend the state labor commissioner form a board of 
inquiry 
a board of inquiry usually formed during a strike is used to 
air differences between disputing parties and help them resolve 
their problems it has subpoena power but no enforcement power 
the daily news is involved in contentious negotiations with the 
10 unions making up the allied printing trades council over 
contracts that expired in march 
one of the first steps toward a board of inquiry is to get at 
least one of the parties in a dispute to say it wants a board 
the council adopted a unanimous resolution july 3 supporting a 
board because it said in a statement efforts to effect 
voluntary settlement of the disputes at the daily news have been 
unsuccessful 
the unions complain among other things that the hired 
negotiators are not familiar with operations at the news that the 
news is trying to eliminate the unions and that strikes or 
lockouts are feared 
john t sloan the papers vice president for human resources 
did not return telephone calls seeking comment his secretary 
referred a reporter to a statement sloan made earlier that the news 
favored facetoface talks without outside participants 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
newspapers could be liable in some instances for 
the acts of their delivery people the arizona supreme court said 
july 3 
the decision came on a lawsuit filed by william santiago a 
motorcyclist injured in a 1986 collision with frank frausto who 
was delivering sunday editions of the arizona republic 
trial judge daniel nastro of maricopa county superior court 
ruled that santiago could not sue the republics corporate parent 
phoenix newspapers inc because frausto was an independent 
contractor and not a pni employee 
the supreme court in its 50 decision said nastro should have 
let a jury decide the question because there was conflicting 
evidence as to fraustos relationship to pni 
a jury could infer that frausto was an employee because 
pni involved itself with the details of delivery received directly 
all customer complaints and changes so as to remove much of 
fraustos independence retained broad discretion to terminate and 
relied heavily on fraustos services for the survival of its 
business the court said 
the jury also could infer that frausto was an independent 
contractor because he used his own car was subject to little 
supervision provided some of his own supplies and could have 
someone else deliver for him within limits 
fraustos contract with pni specifically said that he was an 
independent contractor not an employee 
but the court said contract language does not determine the 
relationship and that juries must look to such factors as the 
extent to which the workers set their own hours and working 
conditions their degree of specialization who pays for the 
material how long the relationship lasts whether pay varies with 
the work how important the work is to the employers bottom line 
and how the parties to the contract see their relationship 
 
</TEXT>
