<TEXT>
a state appeals court has overturned 
32500 in damages awarded to a santa cruz man who sued a womens 
group for libel after its newsletter named him as a wouldbe rapist 
without proof 
in a ruling june 27 the 6th district court of appeal said the 
trial judge failed to tell the jury that it had to find negligence 
by santa cruz women against rape before awarding damages for libel 
it also said the jury should have been told that a deliberate or 
reckless falsehood was required for punitive damages which made up 
most of the award 
a lawyer for steven carney whose damages were reversed by the 
ruling said july 2 that he looked forward to a new trial 
well get a better verdict said attorney david sabih 
negligence is failure to investigate they admitted they never 
investigated this girls complaint 
sabih said the center had stopped publishing the names of 
alleged rapists in its newsletter based solely on the statements of 
the centers clients the practice that led to the suit 
the court said a 19yearold drug store coworker of carneys 
identified as karen w came to the center in june 1984 and told 
staffers that carney and another man had taken advantage of her the 
previous night after she had passed out drunk five months later 
the center printed carneys name description and workplace in its 
newsletter under the heading assaultattempted rape 
the center admitted it had relied solely on the womans account 
and its observations of her behavior and had not tried to contact 
carney or investigate in any other way the court said 
before the trial karen w sent carney a letter part of a 
settlement of suits they had filed against each other saying she 
had not been raped or had sex with either man 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a bill passed by the state assembly on 
july 5 would shorten the period for a political candidate to demand 
and get a correction of libelous campaign ads 
under current law a person cannot sue for general damages if he 
demands a correction within 20 days and that correction is 
published or broadcast within three weeks of the demand 
the bill would give the person who believes he or she is libeled 
or slandered seven days to demand a correction the other side 
would then have seven days to publish a correction in substantially 
as conspicuous a manner as were the statements claimed to be 
libelous 
</TEXT>
