the power of an odor to stimulate memory 
familiar to anybody who has suddenly thought of a longlost lover 
after getting a whiff of perfume or cologne has proved itself in a 
research laboratory 
college students who smelled chocolate during a word exercise 
and again the next day when asked to remember their answers did 
better than others denied the memoryevoking aroma 
such an odorbased memory strategy could help students studying 
for multiple exams or airline pilots training for emergencies said 
researcher frank schab 
his work provides the first firm scientific evidence that odors 
can help bring back memories said brian lyman of the monell 
chemical senses center in philadelphia 
