<TEXT>
koncinski is one of only four yearround staff members at the 
mccall base he is the loft foreman the supervisor of parachutes 
which undergo some rugged use the others are a director of 
training a loadmaster who sees to equipment and cargo and 
hurricane davis the base manager 
mccall with 70 jumpers is the largest of nine bases in idaho 
montana northern california oregon washington and alaska but 
during the fire season the jumpers move from base to base depending 
on where the action is at one point last year 167 jumpers were 
camped at mccall and on four different occasions all were fighting 
fires none in reserve 
except for the smattering of administrators who also jump all 
smokejumpers hire on only for the fire season most return year 
after year they are a varied bunch at mccall three doctors a 
lawyer a professor of entomology a veterinarian a high school 
principal several teachers all must pass a rigorous physical test 
each summer to requalify their average age is 32 
if they have one thing in common it is a love of the outdoors 
of nature keep a light hand on the land is their dictum 
its quite a feeling said roger staats a 25yearold 
jumper from colorado to stand on a ridge over a canyon and think 
you might be the only person to have set foot on that spot i dont 
want to leave any evidence that i was there 
once in the wilderness we found a little snowmelt stream 
nearby and we diverted it to help catch the fire when the fire was 
out we put the stream back where it was 
most like koncinski who was a forestry student at the 
university of connecticut learned about the smokejumpers when they 
took summer jobs as forest service firefighters to earn college 
tuition 
about 500 hopefuls apply each year for only a handful of 
openings all must have experience fighting wildfire but theyll 
tell you that veteran smokejumpers and their own experience has 
taught them more than they ever learned on a fire line 
they learn that when lightning hits a tree the tree explodes in 
a spray of burning faggots or else it spirals down the trunk 
peeling bark like a corkscrew down to the roots setting the 
forest undergrowth ablaze 
they learn that a few spruce trees are more dangerous than a 
stand of lofty pines more apt to spread fire to the treetops 
because their downswept boughs reach the burning undergrowth they 
know that aspens are slow to catch fire and that the sage that 
perfumes a mountain meadow contains oils that flash off like 
gunpowder 
we get a look at the fire from the air so thats an 
advantage said jerry ogawa you have an idea of what youre 
getting into how youre going to attack it 
ogawa 44 is a fourthgrade teacher in oregon in the winter and 
a smokejumper the past 24 years at mccall he has made about 160 
jumps on fires and another 160 for practice hes seen it all and 
is one of mccalls qualified spotters the person in charge aboard 
the drop airplane 
heres how he explains the procedure 
lightning hits tree mountaintop lookout spots fire bell rings 
in the mccall ready room within 10 minutes 12 jumpers are airborne 
aboard a dc3 which is as old as jerry ogawa and maybe even as 
durable 
we circle the fire size it up check the terrain select a 
landing target and look for a route for the jumpers to pack out to 
where somebody can pick them up i once had to walk 22 miles 
then we drop streamers to tell us which way the chutes will 
drift to be on target you can only steer them so much in this 
terrain if the fire is on a ridge and you miss the target you 
could wind up halfway down a nearvertical slope and get to the 
fire too late 
the streamers also tell us our altitude we jump at 1500 
feet the plane has an altimeter of course but this country is 
all ridges and canyons and we need to be sure we need for those 
streamers to hit the ground in one minute and a half or we adjust 
up or down 
the spotter decides how many jumpers it will take to do the 
job two four six we go in pairs everybody likes twoman fires 
the best we send as few as possible so as many as possible will be 
available for other fires 
they jump land and radio back that they are safe then we 
make another pass at about 500 feet and drop their fire packs one 
pack for each two men these contain their tools just a 
breakdown shovel and a pulaski a combination axe and grubbing hoe 
and their sleeping bags first aid kit water food for six meals 
then theyre on their own 
the jumpers carry a 150foot letdown rope in one leg pocket in 
case they land in a tree which is not uncommon in fact it is 
sometimes preferred 
tall grass in a mountain clearing may look inviting but 
underneath lurk stumps and snags and rocks that can break a leg 
many a smokejumper has trusted a padded suit and crash helmet and 
steered instead for the nearest tree later he must climb the tree 
to fetch the parachute no selfrespecting smokejumper would come 
home without his chute 
they wear crash helmets with steel mesh face masks and jump 
suits heavily padded from ankle to neck these they shed on the 
ground and fight the fire in jeans and a hardhat but get this 
they draw no hazard pay for jumping into those trees and stumps and 
rocks hazard pay for these government workers begins only when 
they start fighting the fire same as if they arrived by truck 
the risks of smokejumping are obvious but the jumpers do not 
dwell on them 
sixyear jumper jim duzak a paramedic only reluctantly tells 
about the time he carried out barry koncinski after barry suffered 
two broken ankles or about the night that huge rocks loosened by 
burnedout tree roots tumbled down the mountain and broke both 
arms and a leg of a fellow jumper 
it took all night to pack him out five miles duzak recalls 
and no one mentions the fire in mann gulch mont where 13 
smokejumpers perished and three escaped but that was back in 1949 
when the service was in its infancy 
shared risk though along with unlimited confidence in one 
another account in large measure for the obvious camaraderie that 
has lured these adventurous and resourceful men and since 1982 
women back to americas great basin each year for half a century 
its a big fraternity a family said hurricane davis we 
think were among the best wait he said strike think and 
among were the best 
</TEXT>
