editors note along the border between south lebanon and 
israel israeliarmed lebanese christian militiamen help defend the 
jewish state against attacks by palestinian guerrillas an ap 
correspondent who recently spent a week inside what is known as 
the zone filed this report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the gulleys and hills of this killing 
ground echo with gunfire most days as guerrillas attack a lebanese 
border zone occupied by israel and its militia ally the south 
lebanon army 
at night parachute flares fired to spot infiltrators cast a 
ghostly light around the hilltop forts manned by the 3000strong 
sla mostly christians 
theyre human sandbags says an officer of the united 
nations peacekeeping force they absorb the raids and take the 
casualties rather than the israelis in return the israelis arm 
them pay the bills and keep them in power 
the militia backed by some 1200 israeli soldiers and hundreds 
of security agents man the socalled security zone a strip of 
lebanese territory that runs north of the border from the 
mediterranean coast in the west to the foothills of mount hermon in 
the east 
it costs israel 3 million a month to support the sla but for 
them its money well spent in the last 4 years nearly 200 
militia fighters have been killed and some 600 wounded defending 
israel in south lebanon where guerrillas fight among themselves as 
much as they do the israelis 
hundreds of palestinian guerrillas and lebanese leftist and 
moslem irregulars have been killed or wounded 
no israeli civilian has been slain in guerrilla raids from south 
lebanon since 1985 although the guerrillas still occasionally fire 
ineffectual rocket salvos into northern galilee 
still more than 30 israeli soldiers have been killed in the 
security zone since it was established in mid1985 that was when 
the israelis withdrew after three years of occupying a large chunk 
of lebanon harried all the way by suicide bombers and leftist and 
moslem guerrillas 
the zone 6 to 10 miles deep joins a finger of territory held 
by the sla that runs north to the christian mountain town of 
jezzine 15 miles above the israeli border 
israel pays the sla salaries and covers all our expenses 
says gen antoine lahd the silverhaired retired lebanese army 
officer who commands the sla israel provides us with all our 
needs we protect the zone and israels northern borders 
lahd a maronite catholic says his objective is a normal 
relationship of good neighborliness with israel theyre our 
neighbors we dont see any point in fighting them 
the israelis invaded lebanon in june 1982 because palestinians 
attacked them from lebanon he says 
its our duty to prevent anyone the palestinians iranians 
and others from using our land to attack israel lahd said in an 
interview at his heavily guarded villa in the slas headquarters 
complex in the mountain town of marjayoun 
this way we keep our land free and we avoid israeli reprisal 
attacks against terrorists on our land 
the israelis insist they do not want to stay in south lebanon 
the sla emerged from a group of christians armed by the israelis 
in 1976 to combat palestinian guerrillas lahd took over command of 
the sla in 1984 after its leader a renegade lebanese army major 
named saad haddad died of cancer 
lahd 62 was wounded in november 1988 when a woman member of 
the lebanese communist party who had a job as his wifes dance 
instructor shot him in an assassination attempt 
the lebanese government considers lahds force to be agents of 
the israelis who occupy lebanese territory and show no sign of 
withdrawing 
but one day when the middle east crisis is over and the 
problem of lebanon has been settled well be integrated into the 
regular lebanese armed forces lahd says given his cooperation 
with israel that remains to be seen 
the sla is armed with obsolete israeli tanks artillery and 
other weaponry much of it captured from the arabs lahd says the 
militia is divided into two brigades of 1500 fighters most of 
them deployed along the 72mile northern edge of the enclave 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900709-0190 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
lahds spokesman caesar saqr says the zone was attacked 353 
times by infiltrators roadside bombs or artillery mortar and 
rocket bombardments last year almost one a day 
all the infiltration attempts were intercepted and dealt with 
in the security zone saqr says 
the sla fighters have a reputation for poor discipline and 
brutality most moslems and not a few christians consider them 
israeli mercenaries 
an sla private is paid 150 a month six times the average wage 
in other parts of lebanon and a second lieutenant gets 240 
lahd has sought to recruit shiites to give his army a sectarian 
mix but many of those defected 
the israelis say that better training by israeli instructors has 
improved the slas discipline and reliability 
the israelis in the zone are deployed primarily in strategic 
hilltop fire bases bristling with electronic surveillance equipment 
the israeli air force regularly attacks palestinian and lebanese 
guerrilla bases to avenge major attacks israeli troops with tanks 
and helicopter gunships often strike out of the zone on punitive 
raids seizing moslem suspects 
the israelis are not an occupation army lahd insists you 
dont see them in the streets or villages of the security zone 
they dont interfere with the population 
but shin beth israels security service operates in the zone 
along with an estimated 750 lebanese agents and informers un 
officials say 
most of the estimated 200000 people living in the 
328squaremile enclave are moslems the christians total only 
about 69000 and that makes them nervous 
their numbers have recently been swollen by some 20000 people 
who fled fighting in the christian enclave north of beirut 
many moslems believe that lahd with israels blessing seeks to 
turn the zone into a christian ministate a perpetual buffer bound 
economically to israel lahd and the israelis deny that 
the israelis and the sla impose tight restrictions to combat the 
guerrillas who include iranianbacked shiite moslem zealots 
prosyrian lebanese and communists 
at entry points into the zone on the lebanese side everyone is 
frisked even cigarette lighters are seized unless theyre the 
transparent plastic variety in case they contain electronic 
devices 
theres no official curfew but few people venture out at night 
you never know when youre going to get caught up in a gun 
battle between the sla and infiltrators said one christian who 
gave his name only as luftallah the israelis open fire 
immediately on drivers who dont pull over when their convoys are 
on the move 
like many other inhabitants of the zone he pays about 5 to 
anyone wholl ride with him for a day in his pickup truck 
distributing butane gas cylinders luftallah who hails from the 
village of qleiaam explained that every vehicle has to have at 
least two people in it because the israelis are afraid of suicide 
attacks 
the last such attack was on oct 20 1988 when a shiite zealot 
named abdallah atwi detonated his explosivespacked car as he drove 
past an israeli convoy killing himself and eight israelis 
the israelis have tried to set up civil administrations in 
the villages but many moslems refuse to recognize them 
the militiamen sometimes aided by shin beth agents regularly 
raid shiite and sunni moslem villages rounding up suspected 
guerrilla sympathizers 
the sla prison at khiam south of marjayoun holds some 350 arabs 
mostly lebanese shiites in the former french colonial fortress 
men who have been released from khiam claim that torture beatings 
and malnutrition are commonplace 
the inmates of khiam have become part of the longrunning drama 
of western hostages held by iranianbacked shiites in lebanon the 
kidnappers have said they will free hostages if israel releases the 
khiam prisoners many of whom have been held as long as some of the 
western captives 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900709-0191 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
every morning some 2500 lebanese 
mostly women cross into israel through what they call the good 
fence to go to work 
to the lebanese government theyre traitors but for many of the 
200000 people living in the israelioccupied region of south 
lebanon working in the jewish state means survival 
the 1 million a month they earn is the economic lifeline for 
the region that has been shunned by lebanons central government 
since the israelis established the socalled security zone five 
years ago as a buffer against guerrilla attacks 
the government in beirut considers us collaborators with the 
enemy said a shiite moslem woman who gave her name only as 
zainab as she underwent security checks at kfar kila on her way to 
work as a maid at an israeli hotel 
beirut doesnt help us but they dont like us working in 
israel either we have no choice 
gen antoine lahd commander of the israeliarmed south lebanon 
army said if beirut sent us 1 million every month id stop 
anyone working in israel 
the israelis set up the fence in 1976 the year after lebanons 
civil war started when they began cooperating with southern 
christians to curb attacks by palestinian guerrillas based in the 
region 
the lebanese who work in israel earn an average 350 a month 
four times the minimum monthly wage set by the lebanese government 
most of the women work in hotel kitchens small factories or 
textile plants the men generally work as gardeners or in 
construction 
by allowing lebanese to work in the jewish state the israelis 
make the zone dependent on them economically but it also makes it 
easier to recruit men for the 3000strong sla which backed by 
some 1200 israeli soldiers blunts attacks by guerrillas 
only sla personnel can send a wife a mother or a member of 
their family to work in israel said a lebanese police officer 
who declined to be identified 
the zone is under constant attack by guerrillas while they have 
some support particularly among the shiite moslems many 
inhabitants of the zone wish the guerrillas would go away 
the israelis are my enemy said a schoolteacher who 
identified himself only as hassan but if we allow them to fight 
israel from here the israelis will employ scorched earth tactics 
the people who live here have nowhere to go 
the policeman is one of about 200 lebanese police officers who 
operate in the zone along with scores of administrative and 
educational personnel all local people 
we only have civil duties the officer said the israelis 
through their various agencies control political security 
deputy mayor mahfouz mahfouz of marjayoun the zones 
capital lamented 
were the forgotten ones the government doesnt send us 
anything not stationary heating fuel nothing i even had to buy 
the lebanese flag in my office with my own money 
</TEXT>
