<TEXT>
this is a very important week in economic 
affairs not just because of the economic summit in houston but 
because the weeks dosage of key indicators will be released on 
friday the 13th 
sensible people understand that the coincidence doesnt ensure 
the figures will be bad but such a degree of uncertainty exists 
these days that you cannot be complacent securities markets have 
been shaken by less 
uncertainty is the enemy of economic progress it is a malady 
made worse in modern times by computers that spit out positive data 
one day negative the next it is the allpurpose explanation for 
lethargy in securities markets 
these days it reigns over all 
it rises just before budget deficit or trade figures are 
released and it is exacerbated every time a statement is released 
about the progress of trade talks with japan will the japanese 
live up to their agreements 
the celebration over politicaleconomic events in europe is 
muted by the uncertainty of what might follow it rises every time 
another blue chip company reports a decline in earnings as many of 
them have been doing lately 
uncertainty received a megashot in recent days when president 
bush indicated he might renege on what had been a nearcertainty 
that the phrase tax increase would not escape his lips will 
he or wont he 
and will alan greenspan chairman of the federal reserve board 
allow interest rates to fall as so many wall street analysts have 
been forecasting or perish the thought might he allow them to 
rise as some analysts fear 
theres that savings and loan fiasco to deal with it might be 
the ultimate statistical uncertainty what had been thought to be a 
50 billion disaster then a 500 billion catastrophe might become 
a trilliondollar tragedy 
hearing this an unnerved financial analyst was thought to say 
something to the effect that you havent heard anything yet some 
banks and insurers he said are in bad shape they might survive 
he said but you cant be certain 
all these concerns must be viewed in the context of the 
allencompassing macro uncertainty which is whether the economy 
will fall into recession or instead grow slightly or perhaps even 
embark on a boom 
who really knows 
what is known is that you can never be certain that interest 
rates and prices will fall in a recession no matter what economic 
theory states 
and you are warned almost every day if the economy expands 
instead then higher prices and higher interest rates are a real 
threat 
