the agency said it would not disclose the names of the companies 
or the amount of money they will pay until aug 28 but a statement 
released by the commission said the companies will make the largest 
monetary payment to the maritime commission in its 29year history 
we realized from the beginning that only a strong deterrent 
would prevent unlawful practices in pacific trade acting 
commission chairman james j carey said in the statement this 
agreement goes a long way toward assuring future compliance with 
the shipping act of 1984 
the largest previous settlement with the commission was 4 
million made in the late 1970s said seymour glanzer director of 
the agencys bureau of hearing counsel glanzer declined in a 
telephone interview to reveal the identity of the companies how 
many are involved whether they are us or foreign lines and the 
amount of money in the settlement 
violations of the shipping act or commission regulations can 
result in penalties of up to 25000 per shipment 
a source familiar with the agreement said it involved between 
four and 10 companies 
the companies allegedly charged rates to ship cargo that were 
less than the official tariffs they had previously filed with the 
commission glanzer said 
in addition to paying the penalties the settlement requires 
them to fully disclose alleged wrongful or questionable rate 
practices including rebates and inaccurate descriptions of cargo 
the companies also have agreed to participate in a new 
compliance accord that involves stronger policing of cargo rates by 
the shipping industry 
a similar settlement covering cargo trade in the atlantic for 
2 million took effect in 1987 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

