three members of an underground group of computer 
hackers that bilked telecommunications companies of money and 
credit information pleaded guilty to federal conspiracy charges 
monday 
the three are members of the legion of doom a closely knit 
group of about 15 computer hackers operating in georgia texas 
michigan illinois florida new york and other states said us 
attorney joe whitley 
whitley said the group disrupted telecommunications stole 
computer source codes and information stole credit information and 
fraudulently obtained money and property 
in may authorities in indiana who prosecuted a teenager 
involved with the group called it an elite group of hackers that 
accepted only the nations best computer moles 
the juvenile who was not identified pleaded guilty to 11 
counts of fraud and agreed to testify against the atlanta men in a 
trial scheduled to begin monday 
instead the three pleaded guilty they were identified as adam 
e grant 22 and robert j riggs 22 both of atlanta and 
franklin e darden jr 24 of norcross 
federal authorities charged that between sept 10 1987 and 
july 21 1989 the three men illegally accessed various bellsouth 
co computer systems and obtained valuable information that they 
distributed to other hackers 
grant and darden also monitored private telephone conversations 
whitley said in a statement 
they were charged with conspiracy to commit computer fraud wire 
fraud access code fraud and interstate transportation of stolen 
property 
darden and riggs pleaded guilty to one count of conspiracy each 
and face a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a 250000 
fine 
grant pleaded guilty to possessing 15 or more bellsouth access 
devices with intent to defraud and faces a possible 10 years in 
prison and a 250000 fine 
a spokesman for bellsouth scott ticer said the operation cost 
his company about 15 million most of it for investigating and 
changing access codes 
