cotton futures prices fell sharply monday on the new york cotton 
exchange extending a slide that began last week and represents the 
markets steepest drop this year 
on other commodity markets energy futures rallied sugar 
plummeted precious metals were lower grains and soybeans were 
mixed and livestock and meat futures were mixed 
cotton futures fell 08 cent to the permitted daily limit of 2 
cents with the contract for delivery in october off 2 cents at 
7674 cents a pound the july contract expired at 90 cents a pound 
the retreat followed limit losses in most contracts on friday 
analysts attributed the selloff to profittaking after a sixmonth 
rally that boosted the price of cotton for nearterm delivery from 
about 66 cents in early january to a high of 939 cents a pound on 
july 5 
this has been a bull market like we havent seen in years and 
years said ernest simon a cotton specialist with 
prudentialbache securities inc in new york 
he said prices had been driven steadily higher over the past six 
months by strong domestic and international demand for us cotton 
and more recently by poor growing weather in the high plains of 
texas where it has been much too dry and much too hot for weeks 
on end 
a surge in wholesale gasoline prices led energy futures higher 
on the new york mercantile exchange 
analyst stephen w platt of dean witter reynolds inc said 
gasoline prices continued to firm in the aftermath of fridays 
explosion and fire at an arco chemical co plant in texas 
traders bought on the assumption that temporary shortages of a 
gas additive produced by the plant could disrupt availability of 
premium gas grades in some areas platt said 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 27 cents 
lower with august at 1658 a barrel heating oil was 53 cent to 
63 cent higher with august at 4890 cents a gallon unleaded 
gasoline was 20 cent to 144 cents higher with august at 5685 
cents a gallon 
