<TEXT>
with west germany and france in the lead the 
prosperous western democracies are gearing up for a 
multibilliondollar effort to protect mikhail gorbachev from the 
economic morass that threatens his hold on soviet power 
long lines and restive consumers give ample evidence that 
gorbachevs economic reforms need an infusion of imagination and 
cash 
inability to keep food stores stocked has already forced moscow 
to spend an extra 3 billion rubles 500 million on food 
imports the white house says half the soviet grain crop goes bad 
before it gets to the marketplace 
gorbachev has asked the west for financial and technical 
assistance and the subject dominated the first day of this weeks 
economic summit the summit leaders are split down the middle on 
how to proceed and apparently agreed monday to allow one another 
to go their own way 
west germany alone hopes to make 31 billion in loans 
available along with france and italy it is pressing for an 
overall western aid package in excess of 15 billion 
if we dont decide now to help the soviet union there is a 
risk that there will be no progress no further reform of the 
soviet political system frances francois mitterrand said in the 
opening summit session his remark was relayed by spokesman hubert 
vedrine 
president bush and margaret thatcher of britain lead the goslow 
faction they question the wisdom of pumping in aid without more 
soviet reform and the americans are emphasizing instead their 
willingness to provide technical assistance to improve soviet 
agriculture and transportation 
nonetheless they have delivered gorbachev a substantial gift by 
not trying to block the others the summit nations are planning to 
act in concert in dispatching teams of bankers and other experts to 
assess soviet needs perhaps setting the stage for a more 
substantial american commitment 
every country has its own kind of legitimate interests and 
concerns marlin fitzwater the white house spokesman said we 
do not question them 
seventythree years after the russian revolution soviet 
officials emphasized on monday that assistance could not carry 
western conditions we arent taking orders said gorbachev 
aide georgy shaknazarov 
but bush has three main objections to offering direct aid the 
soviets heavy military spending their sending 5 billion a year 
in aid to marxist cuba and their slow pace in adapting to 
capitalistic ways 
it was vaguely possible that summit leaders might attempt to set 
specific conditions concerning one or more of those problems before 
approving aid 
the soviets are open about their need for western help i feel 
it would be advantageous for us and the west said foreign 
minister eduard shevardnadze he said he disliked the term aid 
preferring credit technical cooperation personnel training 
joint ventures and joint projects a message welcome to bush 
only a year ago the united states britain france canada 
west germany japan and italy stepped gingerly into these uncharted 
waters and decided to help poland and hungary the soviet union 
presents a far more difficult decision 
from the french delegation meanwhile came a statement of 
renewed determination to bolster gorbachev and the soviet economy 
with all aid that is serious and useful 
failure of perestroika could mean gorbachevs downfall and begin 
an era of instability across the soviet union where would the west 
be asked brian mulroney of canada if they chuck him out 
us officials make this kind of case for moving slowly 
it is impossible to keep tabs on assistance many of the 
billions could be diverted to the red army where the generals and 
gorbachev do not always see eye to eye 
it doesnt make sense to send billions to the soviets while 
they are sending billions to cuba a state whose interests often 
collide with the united states mulroney agrees with bush that 
soviet aid to cuba is profoundly unacceptable and he said 
canada was willing to provide trade credits not direct assistance 
the soviet economy is so messed up that immediate aid will be 
wasted treasury secretary nicholas brady said monday theres no 
sense in pouring money into a system that isnt ready to receive 
it 
