<TEXT>
president bush argued very forcefully with 
his summit partners monday to phase out billions of dollars in farm 
subsidies but there were few signs that european leaders would heed 
the arguments 
bush has made reaching a compromise on the farm issue a top 
priority at this weeks sevennation economic summit believing 
that a resolution is critical to breaking a deadlock in a fouryear 
effort to overhaul the global trading system 
but officials of the 12nation european community which 
participates in the annual economic summit gatherings insisted 
that houston was not the place to negotiate on the trade issue 
throwing into doubt whether the administration will be able to 
achieve a hopedfor breakthrough 
the united states has much at stake in the global trade talks 
because they offer the promise of greatly expanding markets for 
us farmers and businesses more exports would help reduce 
americas 100 billion annual trade deficit 
the trade talks known as the uruguay round for the country 
where they were launched in 1986 have reached a virtual stalemate 
over the divisive farm issue 
bush brought up the trade negotiations in a string of oneonone 
sessions with world leaders before the summit officially got under 
way monday 
white house chief of staff john sununu told reporters that bush 
believed resolution of the trade dispute is critical it should 
and must be done 
the agricultural question was taken up in the first round of 
talks between the leaders on monday afternoon at rice university 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters the 
administration fears that the entire global free trade talks will 
falter without a resolution of the farm issue 
bush is making the point very forcefully to his summit 
partners that this is an enormously important activity 
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter told reporters 
yeutter said that so far the european community has not been 
engaged in the process 
but the european community contends that between 2 million and 3 
millin european farmers could lose their jobs if the subsidies 
which support their lessefficient operations were eliminated 
the ec known as the common market is represented at the 
economic summit by ec president jacques delors who met with bush 
before the summit began to discuss their differences 
bush took a tough stance telling delors that the political 
leaders needed to exhibit courage to resolve the issue an ec 
official said 
it was quite hard on agriculture said the official who 
spoke on condition that his name not be used 
aides said bush also discussed agricultural policy in his 
meeting with french president francois mitterrand and west german 
chancellor helmut kohl the two leaders with the strongest 
opposition to total elimination of farm subsidies 
kohl indicated to bush that a draft negotiating paper on the 
agricultural issue unveiled recently by the chairman of the 
negotiating group aart de zeeuw a former dutch agricultural 
official could be the basis for breaking the deadlock hans klein 
kohls spokesman told reporters 
yeutter said kohls stance was mildly encouraging but 
another us official who spoke on condition that his name not be 
used said that it was unclear whether kohls comments really 
signified a new willingness to negotiate 
kohl is particularly crucial to resolving the agricultural 
question because bush is unlikely to push too hard for concessions 
if the german leader digs in his heels because of upcoming german 
unification elections 
those elections will occur around the time negotiators are 
scheduled to meet in brussels for the final bargaining session to 
complete the uruguay round of trade talks the talks are being 
conducted under the auspices of the 97nation general agreement on 
tariffs and trade 
in the opening session kohl spoke about the need to conclude 
the global trade talks successfully telling the other leaders 
we should give the negotiators a positive signal and a 
political orientation that we all jointly stand for strengthening 
the gatt 
canadian foreign minister joe clark said he believed after 
discussions with common market officials that some ground can be 
found for forward movement 
us trade representative carla hills told reporters that the 
united states hoped to achieve a commitment from the summit 
countries to use the de zeeuw paper as the basis for working out a 
final agreement but she said it was not certain whether even this 
position would overcome european resistance 
in addition to phasing out farm subsidies the united states has 
an ambitious goal of expanding global trade rules to include about 
1 trillion in trade not now covered by the gatt the world body 
which policies trade disputes 
the us proposal would result in the elimination of barriers to 
trade in the highgrowth area of banking and other services where 
us companies are extremely competitive american negotiators are 
also pushing to extend gatt rules to cover better enforcement of 
trade and copyright piracy which is estimated to cost american 
companies 60 billion in lost sales each year 
in all of these issues agriculture is seen as the key because 
third world countries have balked at agreeing to us proposals on 
expanding gatt coverage unless they win expanded markets for their 
farm products 
</TEXT>
